DESIGN PRINCIPLE: drift intentionally provides NO command to reset, acknowledge, or dismiss multiple closures at once. `drift reset &lt;hash&gt;` accepts exactly ONE closure per invocation — there is no `--all`, no glob, no multi-arg form, and none will be added. This friction is deliberate and is the whole point of the tool: a bulk reset would let an LLM blindly mark everything as reviewed without actually reviewing the changes, which would make drift useless as a spec-code sync tool. The intended workflow is: `drift todo` (see which closures drifted) → `drift diff --all` (review every closure's changes in one pass) → `drift reset &lt;hash&gt;` (resolve ONE closure at a time, after reviewing it). The one-closure-at-a-time reset is the enforcement point: the reset case dispatches to orch.ResetClosure with exactly args[1] (hash) — a single string, never a slice. See principles.friction.